  "body": "Special thanks to @adlerjohn  for initial discussions on this.\r\n\r\nCurrently, to become a validator, one has to make a deposit on the ETH1 chain and have it processed by the beacon chain. Once the deposit is made, a validator has to wait ~6 hours before 1) ETH1 data gets added to a beacon block and then 2) until the potential validator gets processed within 2 epochs.\r\n\r\nThe spec as currently written doesn't take into account the [_gatekeeping attack_](https://arxiv.org/abs/1811.00742) in which individually rational proposers will choose to exclude deposit receipts, as each new validator strictly decreases their rewards. This is because [the total reward scales with the square root of the total balance](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/blob/v0.5.0/specs/core/0_beacon-chain.md#rewards-and-penalties).\r\n\r\nThere are at least 2 independent ways to fix this:\r\n\r\n1. Change the current sub-linear issuance model to a linear issuance model (i.e., set `adjusted_quotient = get_previous_total_balance(state) // BASE_REWARD_QUOTIENT`). Since individual validator rewards no longer decrease with each new validator, there is no incentive to prevent new validators from joining.\r\n1. Have other validators act as whistleblowers and actively monitor the proposer for an epoch in which new validators get onboarded. When censoring occurs, whistleblowers can submit a proof from ETH1 data since the ETH1 chain contains a total ordering of deposits. Deposits may need to be augmented with a nonce, or the timestamp of deposits could suffice. If the proof is correct, the proposer for that epoch gets penalized. Attestors do not need to be penalized as they are not the ones censoring, and we don't want them to abstain from signing a block that provably censors deposit receipts.\r\n\r\nThoughts?",
