    "body": "Thanks @adlerjohn again for discussions on this.\r\n\r\nFirst, I would like to note that the gatekeeping attack and discouragement attacks are different. In the gatekeeping attack, there's no cost for the malicious proposer to censor deposits whereas in discouragement attacks, the malicious proposer incurs some cost to themselves to attack other validators in the protocol. As such, the inv-sqrt issuance does not fix gatekeeping attacks since gatekeeping attacks are free.\r\n\r\nSecond, we can tweak 2) to leverage the fact that ETH1 data is voted on. For this, we need to include additional data in the Merkle proofs from the deposit logs that proves the correct number of deposit logs. Additional logic when voting for the correctness of ETH1 data should include a check that the number of deposit logs being included in a block do in fact match up with the probable number of deposits.",
