    "body": "There are two types of gate-keeping\r\n\r\n1. Validators conspire to prevent new eth1 deposit root from being successfully updated. This requires an attacker from having more than 50% of the proposers during an eth1 voting period which is highly unlikely given a 2/3 honesty assumption. This is potentially easier to conduct in early days of the beacon chain when validation numbers are lower and this is exactly why the `CHAIN_START_DEPOSIT_THRESHOLD` was increased to `65536` full deposits or (~2M ETH). This type of attack is also _very_ easy to detect extra protocol and can be coordinated if actually becomes a problem. This would also show us that our honestly assumption is broken in the early days which is better than finding that out in say phase 2.\r\n2. Validators do not process deposits into the beacon chain. This is almost entirely mitigated by the new addition of enforced deposit processing. If for the current eth1 data deposit root there are unprocessed deposits, a validator _must_ include up to `MAX_DEPOSITS` deposits in their block for the block to be considered valid. A validator that wants to censor incoming deposits via this method can only do so my skipping block proposing (losing profit) and the deposits will certainly just be picked in the next block.\r\n\r\nSee [mandatory deposits](https://github.com/ethereum/eth2.0-specs/pull/758). This seems like a simplified version of your second proposal, right?",
